data.content:
## Migration Analysis

**Pattern identified: Timeout enforcement** — a thread is aborted when it exceeds a time limit.

### What breaks in .NET 8

| API | Problem |
|-----|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |

### Why you can't just delete the abort

The old code **forcibly killed** the thread on timeout. In .NET 8, there is no way to forcibly terminate a managed thread. The work **must cooperate** by checking a `CancellationToken`.

---

### Migrated code (Option A — recommended, task-based)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

**Callers must update** — the `Func<T>` signature becomes `Func<CancellationToken, T>`:

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ComputeResult(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work must check the token
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // check at safe points
    return ComputeResult(ct);
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### Option B — if you can't change the work delegate

If callers pass opaque `Func<T>` that **cannot be modified** to accept a token (e.g., third-party code), cancellation cannot actually stop the work. You can abandon it but the thread keeps running:

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        var task = Task.Run(work);

        if (task.Wait(timeout))
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }

        // Work is still running — we abandon it but cannot kill it
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

> ⚠️ **This is a fire-and-forget leak.** The work continues consuming CPU/resources after timeout. Only use this as a temporary bridge while migrating callers to pass `CancellationToken`.

---

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | What happens | Fix |
|---------|-------------|-----|
| Passing the token but never checking it | Timeout fires, `Cancel()` is called, but work runs to completion anyway | Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints inside loops and between expensive steps |
| Not forwarding token through the call chain | An inner method blocks indefinitely, ignoring cancellation | Every method in the chain must accept and pass the `CancellationToken` |
| Using `Thread.Sleep` inside the work | `Thread.Sleep` ignores the token and blocks until done | Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or `await Task.Delay(ms, token)` |
| Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource` | Timer and callback leaks | Always wrap in `using` |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly | Swallowing cancellation from an unrelated source | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to match only your timeout |

---

### Checklist

- ✅ `Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource` with timeout
- ✅ `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException)`
- ✅ `Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed (not needed)
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` disposed via `using`
- ✅ Callers updated to pass token-aware delegates

**Option A is strongly preferred** — it's the only approach that actually stops the work on timeout.
